<paragraph blockId="3.[94,718,2074,2131]" lastBlockId="3.[794,1417,218,307]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[94,205,2074,2099]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species is known to be viviparous, as females are captured with many first instar larvae inside the abdômen (
<figureCitation box="[963,1027,218,243]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="5.[94,153,744,769]" captionTargetBox="[94,718,204,714]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[94,718,204,714]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 4. Psychoda amazonensis Cordeiro &amp; Bravo, female, dissected abdomen showing characteristic hypovalvae (indicated by arrow) on terminalia and many first instar larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3727791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3727791/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). It can be easily identified by the characteristic hypovalvae (indicated by an arrow on figure 4) and short cerci of the female.
</paragraph>
